The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Software and BPO firm Hexaware Technologies plans to acquire an IT firm in the US or Europe for up to $40 million to expand its overseas operations and expects to close the deal by the end of this year. It will also increase its staff strength in India by 1,000 to take the total headcount to 6,000. The company has started scouting for companies in the US and Europe to expand its enterprise resource planning services in travel, transportation, banking and financial services.

 Tantia Constructions Ltd has bagged orders worth Rs 151 crore for infrastructure projects in the road and rail sector in eastern India. The company has received a CPWD road project worth Rs 113 crore in Bihars Buxar and Bhabua districts. Other projects include an Eastern Central Railway road flyover in Patna. 

 Symantec Corp has launched a centre of innovation in Chennai as part of its move to expand its R amp;D and technical operations in the country. The centre is Symantecs second R amp;D facility in the country which will be able to accommodate more than 1,000 employees.

 Netherlands based Vogels group has entered the Indian market with a range of mounting solutions that can support LCD monitors, VCD and DVD players and home theatres. The company has entered into an alliance with Reliances retail outlets where all its products will be available.

